Patch Set 3:

By default the tomcat will unpack the content of the WAR file (See https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/tomcat-the-definitive/9780596101060/ch03s04.html), in that case logback.xml can be change at runtime. But i still think, the logback shouldn't be part of the WAR, as on deploying new war will overrride the previous logback settings/file and plus the logging approach should be consistence as other applications in SO.

Suggested better solution to the guys in the call to test, which will allow us to move logback out of the WAR file.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> By default the tomcat will unpack the content of the WAR file (See https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/tomcat-the-definitive/9780596101060/ch03s04.html), in that case logback.xml can be change at runtime. But i still think, the logback shouldn't be part of the WAR, as on deploying new war will overrride the previous logback settings/file and plus the logging approach should be consistence as other applications in SO.
> 
> Suggested better solution to the guys in the call to test, which will allow us to move logback out of the WAR file.

I understand the concern you raised here waqas, but unlike the other so pods bpmn infra will be a tomcat application while others are springboot
There are options to change the logging of webapps in tomcat, that we can check further.
Change has been successfully merged by Seshu Kumar M

Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.

How about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1
> 
> > Patch Set 4:
> > 
> > Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.
> 
> How about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.

app_data_path can be set to any arbitrary location, if it's not get set to a path with /opt/onap prefix wouldn't it be vague to have that cfg file in hardcoded path of /opt/onap?

Patch Set 4:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> > Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1
> > 
> > > Patch Set 4:
> > > 
> > > Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.
> > 
> > How about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.
> 
> app_data_path can be set to any arbitrary location, if it's not get set to a path with /opt/onap prefix wouldn't it be vague to have that cfg file in hardcoded path of /opt/onap?

Could be. My point was to potentially avoid confusion about /etc/default/resources.cfg which, for an unware user, might seem to be related to some 'system wide resource configuration (whatever that would be)'. It doesn't make a big difference for me. If you feel that /etc/default location is better - stick to it.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

This is an alternative to the other review, taking the approach of using a pre-created keystore, thus avoiding the need for keytool or bouncycastle.

Note: this keystore is good for 10 years.  A 10-year key might generate a security exception, but this keystore is not included in production code.  Nevertheless, can always regenerate it with just a one year, if desired - simply run gen_truststore.sh & gen_keystore.sh, after modifying the validity period in gen_keystore.sh from 30 days to 365 days.
